<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports U.S. Praise for Ukrainian Nuclear Vote </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0502052394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0451 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0502052394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, February 4 (XINHUA) -- The U.S. today 
described the Ukraine parliament's approval of the First 
Strategic Arms Treaty (Start One) and the related Lisbon 
Protocol as a major non-proliferation achievement. 
  "By approving the Lisbon Protocol, Ukraine is committed to 
accede to the Nonproliferation Treaty in the shortest possible 
time," said White House Spokeswoman Dee Dee Myers. 
  The U.S. comments came after Ukrainian lawmakers voted 260-3 
yesterday to remove conditions they had imposed for approving 
the start one treaty under which Kiev is required to give up all 
its nuclear warheads. 
  Under the agreement, Ukraine, now the world's third nuclear 
power, is to surrender more than 1,600 nuclear warheads 
inherited from the former Soviet Union. 
  "Although the lawmakers voted not to join the nuclear 
Nonproliferation Treaty for the time being, their support for 
start one and the Lisbon Protocol advances the security interest 
of both the United States and Ukraine and represents a major 
non- proliferation achievement," Myers said. 

</TEXT>

