<H3> <TI>   President Clinton Endorses UN Call for Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0702222994 Beijing XINHUA in English 2209 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0702222994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, February 7 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President 
Bill Clinton endorsed today a U.N. call for NATO approval of air 
strikes against those responsible for the Saturday [5 February] 
shelling in Sarajevo that killed 68 civilians and wounded 
hundreds of others. 
  He had long hoped U.N. authorization for military 
retaliation 
for atrocities on the Bosnian Muslim civilians, Clinton said in 
a speech in Houston, Texas. 
  Meanwhile, Secretary of State Warren Christopher said in 
addition to the specific request by U.N. secretary-general, NATO 
allies will discuss a range of options later this week in 
Brussels. 
  Christopher made the remarks after a meeting of senior 
Clinton advisors on the deteriorating situation in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  While responsibility for the Saturday attack, which led to 
the highest single civilian toll since war broke out in the 
Balkan Republic 22 months ago, Christopher said there was a 
strong presumption the the Bosnian Serbs were behind the attack. 
  He did not elaborate what other actions might be taken. 
  Christopher continued consultations with allied officials 
today. He had telephone conversations with foreign ministers of 
five countries, including Britain, France and Canada. 
  The bulk of the U.N. forces on humanitarian missions in 
Bosnia came from these three countries. 
  Clinton again echoed concerns of the countries over possible 
retaliation against their troops, criticizing some lawmakers 
that called for outright air strikes against the Bosnia Serbs. 
  They do not have electorate on the ground, Clinton said. 

</TEXT>

