<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Views President Clinton's Radio Address </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0502180194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1748 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0502180194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, February 5 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President 
Bill Clinton focused his Saturday [5 February] radio address on 
previewing his fiscal 1995 federal budget due to be released 
Monday. 
  Clinton said in his radio address today that his budget 
includes spending cuts in 300 programs, the outright elimination 
of 115 programs and a reduction of more than 100,000 federal 
workers. 
  Seven of 14 cabinet departments will get less money than in 
last year's budget, the President said. 
  Clinton is to unveil 1.5 trillion dollars budget Monday 
while 
in Houston, Texas. A barrage of budget briefings by top 
administration officials are also scheduled for Monday in 
Washington. 
  Clinton used most of the radio address to talk about the 
need 
to continue to create jobs for U.S. workers. 
  Clinton said in his first State of the Union address on 
January 25 that the U.S. private-sector produced 1.6 million 
jobs, more than the total in the previous four years, but added 
that many Americans are still looking for work while wage 
stagnation exists for a lot of employees. 
  The U.S. Labor Department announced Friday that the January 
jobless rate was 6.7 percent as against 6.4 percent in December, 
1993. 

</TEXT>

