<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dalai Lama Expected To Visit in May, Oct </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0802080794 Taipei CNA in English 0726 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0802080794 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Y. C. Tsai] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, Feb. 8 (CNA) -- The Dalai Lama is expected 
to visit Taiwan in May or October in his capacity as a religious 
leader, an elder brother of the Tibetan spiritual leader 
announced at a news conference late Monday [7 February]. 
  Gyalo Thundup, who led a four-member Tibetan group here, 
said 
that the Dalai Lama will meet with President Li Teng-hui, 
Premier Lien Chan, other ranking government officials, and 
religious leaders during his stay in Taiwan. 
  The Dalai Lama, who has received a letter each from 
President 
Li and Premier Lien, admired Taiwan's political and economic 
achievements made during the past four decades, Thundup noted. 
  A possible visit by the Tibetan spiritual leader has stirred 
great interest here since Chao Tze-chi, chairman of the World 
League for Freedom and Democracy, extended a formal invitation 
in 1992. 
  On Beijing's possible reaction, Thundup said that the Dalai 
Lama paid no mind to Mainland China's views toward his planned 
visit to Taiwan, nor did Beijing express opposition to the 
visit. Currently, he pointed out, the Tibetan 
government-in-exile makes frequent contacts with mainland 
authorities. 
  The Dalai Lama has headed the Tibetan Government-in-Exile 
since 1959 when he fled Lhasa, Tibet's capital city. Communist 
Chinese troops launched military campaigns against Tibet in 1949 
and occupied the land in 1951. 
  Meanwhile, Thundup noted, Premier Lien has given the green 
light to the establishment of a liaison office in Taipei by the 
exiled government. The exact time for the office's opening, 
however, has yet to be worked out, he added. 
  The soon-to-be-established liaison office, aiming to 
strengthen cultural exchanges, will be similar to other offices 
around the world, he said. 
  Thundup, who studied at National Chengchi University in the 
1940's and speaks fluent Mandarin, left for home Tuesday morning. 
  Chang Chun-yi, chairman of the cabinet-level Mongolian and 
Tibetan Affairs Commission, said that the government, while 
welcoming the Dalai Lama's visit, is deeply concerned about the 
Tibetans in exile. 
  Statistics show that there are 120,000 exiled Tibetans in 
India, 20,000 in Nepal, 8,000 in Sikkim, and 4,000 in Bhutan. 
  "We hope to work out with the Dalai Lama a solution to the 
problems facing the Tibetan exiles such as education and health 
care," Chang stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-26422 </DOCNO>
