<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military Apologizes for Unfolding Arms Purchase Scandal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0702132594 Taipei CNA in English 1244 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0702132594 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Benjamin Yeh] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, Feb. 7 (CNA) -- A Defense Ministry official 
apologized to the country Monday [7 February] for the unfolding 
arms purchase scandal, which has shrouded the military in a 
cloud of corruption. 
  Lt. Gen. Shih Tzuo-ching, deputy director of the Political 
Warfare Department of the Ministry of National Defense, told a 
press conference that because of the malfeasance of a handful of 
officers, "the military's image has been marred and the nation's 
interest harmed." 
  Several military officers and arms brokers have been 
detained 
for being involved in the murder of Navy Captain Yin Ching-feng, 
whose body was uncovered on Dec. 10. Yin was responsible for 
the navy's arms acquisition unit. 
  The ministry organized a special task force a week after 
Yin's body was discovered, but doubts over the role of the ad 
hoc group have since mounted because little progress has been 
reported in clearing the web of irregularities surrounding the 
incident. 
  Shih denied rumors that the military has been trying to keep 
a low profile on the case because many more ranking officers 
have been implicated. "No direct evidence is available that can 
lead to some suspects being charged," he said. 
  While pledging to bring the case to its just conclusion, 
Shih 
said the Defense Ministry is reviewing its arms procurement 
system to prevent similar scandals in the future. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

