<H3> <TI>   Industry Official Urges Technological Self-Reliance </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0702132694 Taipei CNA in English 1248 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0702132694 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Danielle Yang] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, Feb. 7 (CNA) -- Koo Chen-fu, chairman of 
the Chinese National Association of Industry and Commerce, urged 
domestic manufacturers Monday [7 February] to become 
self-reliant in high technology to help Taiwan decrease its 
dependence on Japan. 
  Koo made the remarks at a meeting of an Economics 
Ministry-sponsored task force that is studying ways to decrease 
the deficit with Japan. 
  Koo said the time for using tax exemptions to stimulate 
investment is over, and that Taiwan must now establish 
independence in high technology in order to get the economy in 
gear. 
  Vice Economic Affairs Minister Sheu Ke-sheng said at the 
meeting that the deficit with Japan can be cut by an industrial 
structure upgrade and by domestic manufacturers producing higher 
quality products in order to tempt Japanese buyers. 
  Hsu said, however, that domestic manufacturers must get over 
their mindset that Taiwan's industries are too weak and reliant 
on Japanese imports of key components and machinery. Until this 
happens, he said, the trade deficit with Japan will continue. 

</TEXT>

