<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Capital Limited to 40 Percent in Public Enterprises </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0502133894 Taipei CNA in English 1250 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0502133894 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Flor Wang] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, Feb. 5 (CNA) -- In an effort to prevent 
foreign investors from totally controlling public enterprises, 
the Ministry of Economic Affairs has announced that foreigners 
will be allowed to own a maximum of 40 percent of any public 
enterprise. 
  Since the government decided to proceed actively with the 
privatization of state-owned concerns to assure continued growth 
and profitability, many foreign firms have been showing strong 
interest in acquiring them. 
  A large Japanese construction firm recently offered a meaty 
price for BES Engineering Corp., but was turned away when BES 
declared the bidding closed to foreigners. 
  The Economics Ministry has targeted Taiwan Machinery 
Manufacturing Corp., Chung Hsin Electric &amp; Machinery Mfg. 
Corp. 
and China Petrochemical Development Corp. for privatization 
before the end of June. Following suit will be Taiwan 
Fertilizer Co., Ltd., Taiwan Power Company, China Steel Corp., 
China Shipbuilding Corp., Taiwan Sugar Corp., and many others 
  Vice Economic Affairs Minister Yang Shih-chien said recently 
that given the vital role many public enterprises play in the 
public's daily life, his ministry will hold firm to its decision 
that public enterprises be kept under the control of Taiwan 
shareholders while they undergo privatization. 
  Sticking to this view is Taiwan Machinery Manufacturing 
Corp., a government property that will soon go private. It has 
included the 40 percent foreign ownership rule in its bid 
instructions. 
  Additionally, a recently published petroleum law regarding 
foreign investment in the local refining industry also orders 
that foreigners cannot hold more than a 30 percent stake in 
those businesses. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

