<F P=100> Science &amp; Technology </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reports on Xichang Satellite Launching Center </TI></H3>
<H4>   Two Satellites Launched </H4>
<F P=102> OW0802115994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1135 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0802115994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, February 8 (XINHUA) -- A powerful carrier 
rocket newly developed by China successfully launched a 
scientific satellite and a simulated satellite into space at 
southwestern China's Xichang launch site this afternoon. 
  The two satellites have now been injected into synchronous 
orbits, according to reports from Xian Satellite Control Center 
and the space measurement vessel "Yuanwang" which was observing 
the satellites at the Pacific. 
  The two satellites were launched by a "Long-March 3A" 
carrier 
rocket, which was developed recently by the Space Industry 
Corporation for launching China's new-type communications 
satellites. 
  The "Long-March 3A" rocket, which was patterned after 
"Long-March 3," is capable of launching a 2.5-ton satellite. 
  The "Long-March 3" rocket, which is capable of launching a 
1.4-ton satellite, ranks fourth in the world in terms of 
launching capabilities. 
  The scientific satellite "SJ-4", carrying six sound 
instruments, will probe charged particles and their effects in 
near-earth space. 
  With the satellite, which was developed by the space center 
under the Chinese Academy of Sciences, Chinese space scientists 
can calculate the parameter of the particles' distribution and 
the necessary electric potential for charging satellite 
batteries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

