<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jiangsu's Industries See Increase in Output Value </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0502105394 Nanjing Jiangsu People's Radio Network in 
Mandarin 2300 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0502105394 </F>
<F P=104>  Nanjing Jiangsu People's Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Mandarin </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Provincial News Hookup" program] </F>
  [Text] Village and town industries in our province again 
made substantial headway in 1993, generating more than 400 
billion yuan in total output value and marketing more than 90 
percent of their products. They held leading positions among 
prefectures and cities nationwide. According to special staff 
correspondent (Yuan Yahe), the total output value of village and 
town industries in Suzhou, Wuxi, Changzhou, and Zhenjiang Cities 
surpassed 3 billion yuan in 1993, representing (?53) percent of 
that of similar industries in the province. Wuxi County, 
Jiangyin City, Wujin City, Zhangjiagang City, and Changshu City, 
known as the five tigers in the southeast, all achieved more 
than 20 billion yuan in output value; this worked out to more 
than 150 billion yuan in total output value, which was the 
highest in southeast Jiangsu. 
  In 1993, our province formally began to implement the 
shareholding and stock cooperative systems in village and town 
enterprises. By the end of November, there were more than 2,600 
experimental enterprises across the province, with shares 
totaling 4.7 billion yuan. Eight new enterprise groups were 
formed, with 5 billion yuan in total fixed assets, or 10 percent 
of the total assets of village and town enterprises across the 
province. Last year saw the fastest economic development for 
our province's village and town enterprises, which achieved more 
than (?55 billion yuan) in sales of export goods, or 
approximately 30 percent of total sales by village and town 
enterprises across the country. More than 4,200 new wholly or 
partly foreign-owned enterprises were set up, bringing the total 
number of such enterprises to 10,000. On average, one out of 
every 10 village and town enterprises in the province was a 
joint venture, and the total amount of contracted foreign 
capital equaled $4 billion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

