<H3> <TI>   Halt of F-16 Production Not To Affect Purchase </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0802131994 Taipei CNA in English 1302 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0802131994 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Debbie Kuo] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, Feb. 8 (CNA) -- The Republic of China 
[ROC]'s planned purchase of F-16 fighters will not be affected 
by US President Bill Clinton's order Monday [7 February] to 
close production lines for the aircraft, the Ministry of 
National Defense said Tuesday. 
  Although the production lines of F-16 fighters for the US 
Air 
Force will be closed, a ministry official said, production for 
foreign military sales will continue. 
  The official quoted a US Air Force spokesman as saying that 
the US Air Force does not want to buy any more F-16s because 
there is already an oversupply of the fighters. 
  The Bush administration agreed to sell Taiwan 150 F-16s in 
1992 defying strong protest from Beijing. The US Government has 
showed many times its commitment to fulfill the contract, the 
official added. 
  The first batch of fighters are expected to be delivered in 
mid-1996, he said. 

</TEXT>

