<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   GATT Membership Would Affect Stock-Breeding, Farmers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0802131794 Taipei CNA in English 1395 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0802131794 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Taipei, Feb. 8 (CNA) -- The stock-breeding and 
food-processing industries are expected to be the most affected 
by Taiwan's entry into the General Agreement on Tariffs And 
trade, the Council for Economic Planning and Development said 
Tuesday [8 February]. 
  A council task force formed to evaluate the impact of GATT 
on 
the local economy said, though, that the rice-growing sector 
won't be as negatively affected as at first thought. Taiwan is 
expected to become a signatory to GATT by the end of the year. 
  Council Vice Chairman Hsue Chih said stock breeders and 
fruit 
farmers will be most affected by GATT membership, as the 
international trade body will require Taiwan to slash tariffs on 
farm products and abolish its quota system and import 
limitations. 
  Taiwan's gradual opening of its rice market, along with 
subsidiary payments to rice farmers, should keep the impact of 
GATT on those farmers to a minimum Hsue said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

