<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shanghai To Mobilize All Economic Sectors To Expand Exports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0502152994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1447 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0502152994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, February 5 (XINHUA) -- Shanghai, China's 
largest port, exported 520 million U.S. dollars' worth of goods 
in January, up 18 percent over the same month in 1993, the 
municipal foreign trade department reported today. 
  An official of the department said that exports from 
Shanghai 
amounted to 7.38 billion U.S. dollars for the whole of 1993. 
The figure represented a nearly 13 percent rise over the year 
before, exceeding the nation's average growth rate for the first 
time in the previous 23 years. 
  The municipal government has decided to mobilize all 
economic 
sectors in Shanghai to expand exports, in a bid to spur the 
city's economic growth in the new year, he said. 
  The manufacturing industry plans to increase exports by at 
least 15 percent this year, he said. 
  To achieve the goal, local manufacturers will try to 
increase 
production of goods popular on the global market, particularly 
new mechanical and electrical products. 
  Furthermore, the municipal government will do everything 
within its power to expand production of 50 kinds of products 
each with an annual export topping five million dollars, and aid 
35 key manufacturers each exporting at least 20 million U.S. 
dollars' worth a year, the official said. 
  Meanwhile, the Pudong New Area, where flexible policies are 
being pursued to encourage Chinese and overseas investors, will 
try to broaden its foreign markets by giving full scope to its 
position as a free trade zone, he said. 

</TEXT>

